      <h1 style="font-size:2.25rem;margin-top:1rem;margin-bottom:0.5rem">Shop Vac Buying Guide for Contractors: How to Choose the Right Wet/Dry Vacuum in 2026</h1>
      <div style="color:#64748b;font-size:0.9rem">June 17, 2026 · 12 min read</div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>A wet/dry shop vacuum is one of the most-used tools on any construction site — yet it's also one of the most misunderstood. Choose the wrong one and you'll be emptying a tiny tank five times a day, fighting with a clogged filter, or dealing with a motor that burns out after three months of drywall dust.</p>
      <p>This guide breaks down everything a contractor needs to know before buying a shop vac: horsepower ratings, tank capacity, filter types, hose sizes, and which features actually matter on a real job site. Whether you're framing houses, doing finish carpentry, or running a renovation crew, the right vacuum saves hours of cleanup time every week.</p>

      <h2>Why Your Shop Vac Choice Matters</h2>
      <p>A good shop vac isn't just about keeping the site clean — it's about productivity. A vacuum with the right capacity and suction power means fewer trips to dump the drum, better air quality for your crew, and less wear on your tools when you use a vac for dust extraction on saws, sanders, and planers.</p>
      <p>The wrong shop vac costs you in three ways: wasted time (constant emptying), wasted money (early motor failure from the wrong filter setup), and wasted effort (poor suction that leaves you going over the same area twice). Getting it right from the start eliminates all three.</p>

      <h2>Horsepower: What the Numbers Actually Mean</h2>
      <p>Shop vac motors are rated in "peak horsepower" — and there's a lot of marketing fluff in those numbers. Here's the reality:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>4–5 Peak HP:</strong> Good for light-duty cleanup, small spills, and general workshop use. Fine for a trim carpenter or electrician. Example: the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07BY8BZ3K?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">DEWALT DXV06P 4 Peak HP 6 Gallon</a> — compact but capable.</li>
        <li><strong>5–6 Peak HP:</strong> The sweet spot for most contractors. Strong enough for heavy debris, wet pickup, and dust extraction on power tools. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07DMNWPKB?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">STANLEY 10 Gallon 6 Peak HP</a> is a classic example of this power class.</li>
        <li><strong>6.5+ Peak HP:</strong> Maximum suction for large job sites, heavy construction debris, and continuous use. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07CBC64DR?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">DEWALT DXV16PA 16 Gallon 6.5 HP</a> delivers enough suction to handle almost anything a construction site can throw at it.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Important: Peak HP is measured at startup, not continuous running. Real-world suction is better measured by <strong>water lift</strong> (inches of lift) and <strong>CFM</strong> (cubic feet per minute of airflow). A 5 HP vac with a well-designed impeller can outperform a 6 HP vac with a poor one. Look at tank size and filter quality as much as the HP number.</p>

      <h2>Tank Capacity: What Size Do You Actually Need?</h2>
      <p>This is the most important decision you'll make. Tank capacity directly affects how often you stop working to empty the drum.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>6–9 gallons:</strong> Best for individual tradespeople — electricians, plumbers, HVAC techs who only need occasional cleanup. Light enough to carry up stairs. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07BY8BZ3K?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">DEWALT DXV06P (6 Gallon)</a> and the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0DWM7KFTZ?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">DEWALT 6-Gallon STEALTHSONIC</a> fit this category perfectly.</li>
        <li><strong>10–12 gallons:</strong> The standard for most construction work. Good balance of capacity and portability. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07DMNWPKB?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">STANLEY 10 Gallon</a> and <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0D9GBM8RF?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">DEWALT 10 Gallon STEALTHSONIC</a> are excellent choices.</li>
        <li><strong>14–16 gallons:</strong> For large job sites and crews. You can go all day without emptying. Heavy but manageable with wheels. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07CBC64DR?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">DEWALT DXV16PA 16 Gallon</a> is the top pick in this class.</li>
        <li><strong>25+ liters (about 6.5 gallons):</strong> The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B09MD77LKP?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">Kärcher WD 5 P</a> at 25L and <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B09MD6NFGL?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">Kärcher WD 2 Plus</a> at 12L offer European-engineered options with stainless steel tanks — great for fine dust and wet pickup on finishing sites.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Wet vs. Dry Pickup: What to Expect</h2>
      <p>Every shop vac on this list handles both wet and dry debris, but there are important differences:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Dry pickup only:</strong> Use a cartridge filter or a HEPA filter bag. For drywall dust, concrete dust, and general construction debris, a bagged setup keeps the filter cleaner longer and makes disposal much easier.</li>
        <li><strong>Wet pickup:</strong> Remove the paper filter and install a foam sleeve filter. The foam won't disintegrate when wet. Always drain and dry the tank thoroughly after wet use to prevent rust and mold.</li>
        <li><strong>Mixed use:</strong> If you switch between wet and dry constantly (common on renovation sites), look for a vac with a quick-change filter system. Brands like DEWALT and Kärcher make this easy with tool-less filter access.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Filtration: HEPA vs. Cartridge vs. Foam</h2>
      <p>Filtration isn't just about clean air — it directly affects how long your shop vac maintains suction power.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cartridge filters:</strong> The standard for most contractor shop vacs. Washable and reusable, with good surface area for fine dust. Available on the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B09V7KDV69?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">DEWALT 9 Gallon DXV09PZ</a> and the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07CBC64DR?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">DXV16PA</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>HEPA filters:</strong> Essential for silica dust compliance on construction sites. OSHA's silica standard (1926.1153) requires HEPA filtration on vacuums used for dust control. The STEALTHSONIC models from DEWALT offer HEPA-level filtration in an ultra-quiet package.</li>
        <li><strong>Foam sleeve filters:</strong> For wet pickup only. Quick to swap in and out. Most shop vacs include one with the purchase.</li>
        <li><strong>Filter cleaning:</strong> A filter that's caked with dust drops suction power by 50% or more. Look for models with a filter-pulsing mechanism (tap the filter clean without removing it) or easy-access filter housings.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Noise Level: Why Quiet Matters on the Job</h2>
      <p>Standard shop vacs run at 85–90 dB — loud enough to require hearing protection and loud enough to make conversation impossible. If you're working in occupied homes or near other trades, noise matters.</p>
      <p>DEWALT's STEALTHSONIC technology changes the game. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0D9GBM8RF?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">DEWALT 10 Gallon STEALTHSONIC</a> and the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0DWM7KFTZ?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">6-Gallon STEALTHSONIC</a> operate at significantly lower noise levels while maintaining strong suction — a huge advantage for remodelers and finish contractors working in occupied spaces.</p>
      <p>If you regularly work in noise-sensitive environments (hospitals, offices, occupied homes), a quiet vac like the STEALTHSONIC or a Kärcher model is worth the investment.</p>

      <h2>Hose Size and Accessories</h2>
      <p>Most contractor-grade shop vacs come with a 2-1/2 inch hose, which is the standard size for connecting to power tools for dust extraction. A 1-7/8 inch hose is available for tighter spaces but restricts airflow.</p>
      <p>Look for a vac that includes:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>At least one smooth hose (glides on floors, doesn't snag)</li>
        <li>A crevice tool for edges and corners</li>
        <li>A brush attachment for finished surfaces</li>
        <li>A wet pickup nozzle with rubber squeegee edge</li>
        <li>Adapter for direct connection to power tools</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Most DEWALT models, the STANLEY 10 Gallon, and the Kärcher units come with comprehensive accessory kits out of the box.</p>

