      <h2>Final Tips Before You Buy</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Match tank size to your typical debris volume.</strong> If you empty the tank more than 3 times per job, you need a bigger vac. If you find the vac half-full at the end of every week, you can go smaller and save space.</li>
        <li><strong>Buy extra filters upfront.</strong> A spare filter means zero downtime when the first one gets clogged. Washable cartridge filters are the most cost-effective option for heavy use.</li>
        <li><strong>Consider the STEALTHSONIC for finish work.</strong> If you do kitchen remodels, bathroom renovations, or work in occupied homes, the noise reduction alone pays for itself.</li>
        <li><strong>Check your tool dust port size.</strong> Most power tools use a 1-1/4 to 1-1/2 inch dust port. A step-down adapter from your 2-1/2 inch hose is often needed and usually included.</li>
        <li><strong>Wheel size matters.</strong> If you're rolling the vac over gravel, rebar, or rough concrete, bigger wheels handle obstacles better. The 16-gallon DEWALT and the STANLEY 10 Gallon both have wheel designs that handle rough terrain.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>A quality shop vac is one of the highest-ROI tools on any job site. It keeps the work area safe, reduces respiratory hazards from dust, speeds up cleanup, and protects your power tools through dust extraction. Choose the right one, take care of it, and it will pay for itself in saved time within the first few months.</p>

